```java
abstract class Bird {
    protected String type;
    protected int numberOfCoconuts;
    protected int voltage;

    public Bird(String type, int numberOfCoconuts, int voltage) {
        this.type = type;
        this.numberOfCoconuts = numberOfCoconuts;
        this.voltage = voltage;
    }

    public abstract String getStatus();
}

class EuropeanSwallow extends Bird {
    public EuropeanSwallow(int numberOfCoconuts) {
        super("EuropeanSwallow", numberOfCoconuts, 0);
    }

    @Override
    public String getStatus() {
        return "average";
    }
}

class AfricanSwallow extends Bird {
    public AfricanSwallow(int numberOfCoconuts) {
        super("AfricanSwallow", numberOfCoconuts, 0);
    }

    @Override
    public String getStatus() {
        return (numberOfCoconuts > 2) ? "tired" : "average";
    }
}

class NorwegianBlueParrot extends Bird {
    public NorwegianBlueParrot(int voltage) {
        super("NorwegianBlueParrot", 0, voltage);
    }

    @Override
    public String getStatus() {
        return (voltage > 100) ? "scorched" : "beautiful";
    }
}

// Usage example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bird europeanSwallow = new EuropeanSwallow(3);
        Bird africanSwallow = new AfricanSwallow(2);
        Bird norwegianBlueParrot = new NorwegianBlueParrot(150);

        System.out.println(europeanSwallow.getStatus()); // Output: average
        System.out.println(africanSwallow.getStatus());  // Output: average
        System.out.println(norwegianBlueParrot.getStatus()); // Output: scorched
    }
}
```

In this refactored code, the `getStatus` method is now defined in each subclass of `Bird`, and the logic for determining the status is encapsulated within those methods. This approach eliminates the need for a large switch statement and makes the code more maintainable and extensible.

